title: For Sale/Trade:  Japanese Naval Officer Kai-Gunto
postcontent:
This is a WW2 Japanese Naval Officer's Kai-Gunto sword. The blade, marked on the nakago (tang) with the Toyokawa Naval Arsenal Anchor in Circle stamp, has a graceful sori (curve) that is reminiscent of the Koto period. The blade is a partially hand forged, oil tempered from stainless steel (as are most blades used in Japanese naval swords) that is robust, solid, strong and clean. It has a very sharp 26" length nagasa (cutting edge) with a chu-suguha (medium width, straight) hamon and chu-kissaki point. The blade's polish is nearly flawless without any forging flaws, bends, chips or nicks. It does have a few, very minor, light, tiny surface scuffs, scratches and rubbings from honest use, but otherwise nothing major. This would rate as a very superb, near mint conditioned blade. The Kai-Gunto mounts are also near mint showing some minor wear from age and WW2 use with a nice aged patina. The tsuba and seppa (and the higher quality sunburst style) are original to the blade and like numbered as E320, the same as the blade nakago. The tsuka has polished, blackened shark skin over its wooden core and then covered with nearly flawless brown silk Ito tape. The saya is covered in polished shark skin (shagreen) that has been lacquered and is in excellent, near mint condition. The blade retention in the saya is via push fit and does not have a retention clip/button. This overall condition of this sword is near mint and would be a great addition to any collection of WW2 Japanese naval swords as most are at the bottom of the Pacific Ocean.

I'm also willing to trade for guns please be an Oregon resident. Please email me if you have any questions.
Thanks

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson "Thunder Ranch" 22-4 Revolver
postcontent:
This is a 45 ACP revolver that will be an awesome home defense or protection firearm!

The revolver comes packaged in a very useful ballistic nylon carrying case emblazoned with the embroidered Thunder Ranch logo.  Inside are 13 full moon clips.  The Model 22 is done up in a really nice polished blue finish, accented by beautifully figured African Cocobolo grips, with a laser-cut Thunder Ranch logo and checkered panels.  These grips are what S&W used to call the “Magna” style and basically followed the lines of the grip frame with the wood coming up over the frame at the rear to form “ears” that helped spread out the surface area a bit to help reduce recoil discomfort.

This revolver is not an exact replica of the Model 1917 or of the commercial .45 Hand Ejector, as it has a shrouded ejector rod, which these guns did not.  It is more like a hybrid of the .45 Hand Ejector Model of 1950 Target, but with fixed rather than adjustable sights.  In fact the left side of the barrel is stamped .45 Cal. Model 1950.  It is a mixture of the old and the new as it had an original-looking cylinder release latch, but also has the latest S&W improvements like the integral cylinder stop, frame-mounted firing pin and internal safety lock.  The front sight is circular-shaped and pinned to a sloping ramp integral to the barrel.  Unlike the older sights, it is a full 1/8” in width and is matte finished to reduce glare.  The fixed rear sight has a wide square-shaped notch which sits inside a trough on the top strap.  Another “oldie” feature is the side-plate on the right side of the frame that is held in place with 4 screws, just like in the good ol’ days.

A couple of other items that make this gun useful as a combat handgun are the medium width trigger with the smooth face; something I definitely prefer over narrow triggers with serrated faces or even wide serrated triggers.  The hammer spur is also wider than what you will find on the service-grade Smiths of years past and it is a compromise as it is midway between a service type and a target-style hammer.  The single-action trigger pull, by the way, on this gun is pure S&W; it has a weight of about 4 pounds and breaks as crisply as snapping a glass rod.  In contrast the double-action pull is smooth and crisp.

This gun is in new unfired condition.  Call if you have any Questions.
GuNworX
Bob Ausborn
REDACTED

http://web.me.com/gunworx/Site/Welcome.html

postcontent:
I have for sale a Mossberg 590 12GA shotgun. 
It has an 8-shot tube, 20" barrel, and adjustable Knoxx recoil-reducing stock. It has a 3" chamber, and with the stock, 3" shells feel like slugs, and slugs feel like birdshot.

postcontent:
This is an American Arms (Uberti Made and marked) .44 mag Target Single Action Revolver, with 6" barrel.  This truly BEAUTIFUL revolver has to be seen (and held) to be appreciated.  These pics do NOT do it justice. 
   It has high definition case hardening on the frame, accented by its solid brass backstrap.  Barrel and cylinder are richly blued.
   Fully adjustable target sights allows you to dial in any load.  Shoots .44 Magnum, along with cheaper and less recoiling, .44 Special ammo.  The .44 Special is similar in power to the .45 Long Colt.  Many consider the .44 to be much more accurate.  The .44 Mag is MUCH more powerful than factory .45 Colt, and has taken all North American big game, including Moose and Alaskan Brown Bear.  Ammo available everywhere, including Walmart.
,   This fine revolver loads and functions just like the original Colt Single Action.  It has the famous four click hammer cocking sound, like the Colt.  The grip feels like the Colt, but is slightly longer, allowing for all fingers on grip.  This makes for a much better, and more solid grip, yet still looks right. Balance is excellent!
   I don't know if this revolver has ever been fired.  Can't tell by looking at it.  To my knowledge, they no longer make the case hardened version, only a less attractive, all blued target model, that lists for over $600.
